Journal from Guada. to Guaymal in Sonora, Continued
1832.  May [?11?]  I have mentioned our leaving Santa Isabel and arriving at Tapucan - in a few words for want of room in my last book.  About a league from Santa Isabel is situated the little hamlet or rancho of Chapalilla which we [?] as the day was near breaking, and for about 3 leagues our road lay [?] a bare ascent gently leading towards a wild mountainous and woody district which we entered about 7 o'clock.  At the entrance to "lo Cuantos" as this tract is called, the road lies along the side of the hill with [?] deep valley or ravines on the left which are covered completely with the Mexican oak which here grows to a considerable size, and a great number of smaller trees and shrubs.  The road for more than three [?]

Note Book. No. 2.
John P. Brodie
May 1832

2.
travelling is dangerous both on account of the bad footing for horses, and the banditti which frequent it.  On leaving the cuanto the country continued mountainous but without wood except on the tops of some of the hills where there are tufts of [?pine?].  I have observed that about this place these tufts are always on the west slope of the hills which are always conical, and the rest of the hill is always covered with grass.  After riding up hill and down dale till 12 o'clock we arrived at the village and Hacienda of San Leonel, romantically and beautifully situated on an elevation with streams of crystalline water on two sides and considerable plantations of wheat, maize, sugar &c surrounding it.
